explanation:
- OS_CHECK_POINTER (macro): This macro is invoked at the top of the function and may expand to statements that read or assign the function parameters (e.g. buffer). To prove the target function does not modify its parameters you must inspect the macro expansion/definition.
- OS_CHECK_SIZE (macro): Same rationale as above for the nbytes parameter — the macro expansion might contain assignments or side-effects that modify the parameter variable.
- OS_ObjectIdGetById (declaration/definition): Determine if this symbol is actually a function or macro wrapper and inspect any macro wrapper for side-effects that could assign to the filedes parameter name (or rebind other parameters). Also needed to confirm it does not expand into code that writes to target parameters.
- OS_LOCK_MODE_REFCOUNT, LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE (macros/constants): These are arguments to OS_ObjectIdGetById; include them to fully understand any macro-based wrapper expansion of OS_ObjectIdGetById that might reference parameter names.
- OS_GenericWrite_Impl (declaration/definition): Inspect its prototype to see whether the buffer argument is declared const or if a macro wrapper alters the buffer parameter (or expands in-place using the caller parameter name). Even if the callee can modify the pointed-to object, we must ensure no macro or inline expansion in the call site reassigns the pointer parameter itself.
- OS_ObjectIdRelease (declaration/definition): Included to inspect for macro wrappers or inlined code that might modify caller parameters (rare but possible via macros).
- osal_id_t, OS_object_token_t, size_t, int32 (typedefs): Needed to know whether parameters are passed by value or via typedefs to pointer types. If a parameter type is actually a pointer typedef, that affects whether the parameter variable itself could be reassigned by macros.
- UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType, UT_Stub_RegisterContextWithMetaData, UT_ExecuteBasicHandler, UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr: These unit-test hook functions appear in the static call graph for OS_TimedWrite (likely inserted via macros). Include them to inspect the macro/instrumentation code paths (their prototypes/uses) to ensure the instrumentation does not reassign or otherwise modify the function parameters as part of stub registration or context capture.

Collecting and inspecting the definitions/prototypes of the above symbols (and macro expansions) is sufficient to determine whether any code in OS_TimedWrite — including expanded macros and any inline/macro wrappers around called routines — performs assignments to the formal parameters (buffer, nbytes, filedes, timeout), which would violate the MISRA rule under review.
